üîê ACL Abuse - Simplified Concept
ACLs (Access Control Lists) control who can do what to AD objects (users, groups, computers).

ACE (Access Control Entry) is an individual permission (e.g., ‚ÄúBuck can reset this user‚Äôs password‚Äù).

DACL = Who has access

SACL = Who tried to access (for logging)

üß† Summary
üéØ What ACLs Do:
They gatekeep access. If you're granted certain rights, you can:

Reset someone‚Äôs password (even if you don‚Äôt know it)

Add yourself to a group (e.g., Domain Admins)

Modify attributes (like SPNs to roast accounts)

Own the object and give yourself full control

üí• Why It Matters:
ACLs are often forgotten or misconfigured. Exploiting them gives you stealthy access, bypassing normal attack paths. They're powerful in mature environments where low-hanging fruit is patched.

üîÅ Got This ‚Üí Do That Workflow (ACL Edition)
üß≠ Initial Enumeration
Got This: BloodHound or PowerView shows access rights over a user, group, or computer object
Do That: Check which ACEs exist and map to these permissions:

Permission Found	Action You Can Take
GenericAll	Full control ‚Äî reset password, add to group, SPN abuse
GenericWrite	Modify attributes ‚Äî set SPN (Kerberoast), add to group
WriteDACL	Modify ACLs ‚Äî give yourself higher rights (like GenericAll)
WriteOwner	Change object ownership ‚Äî then give yourself rights
ForceChangePassword	Reset user‚Äôs password (no old pwd needed)
AddMember	Add controlled user to target group
AddSelf	Add yourself to a group
üéØ Target-Specific Abuse Paths
üë§ Over a User
GenericAll / ForceChangePassword ‚Üí Use Set-DomainUserPassword to reset and take over the user.

GenericWrite ‚Üí Add SPN and perform Kerberoasting.

WriteDACL ‚Üí Grant yourself GenericAll, then reset password.

üë• Over a Group
GenericWrite / AddMember ‚Üí Use Add-DomainGroupMember to add your user to that group.

WriteOwner / WriteDACL ‚Üí Take over the group ACL and escalate access.

üíª Over a Computer
GenericWrite ‚Üí Perform Resource-Based Constrained Delegation.

GenericAll (if LAPS is used) ‚Üí Read LAPS password and get local admin.

WriteDACL ‚Üí Give yourself ability to pull LAPS or access it via RBCD.

üõ†Ô∏è Tool-Based Quick Guide
Tool	Use Case
BloodHound	Visualize ACL abuse paths easily ‚Äî look for edges like GenericAll, AddMember, etc.
PowerView	Enumerate and exploit ACLs from Windows
Set-DomainUserPassword	Reset user password (ForceChangePassword, GenericAll)
Add-DomainGroupMember	Add self to group (AddMember, GenericWrite)
Set-DomainObjectOwner	Abuse WriteOwner
Add-DomainObjectACL	Abuse WriteDACL
GMSAPasswordReader	If you see ReadGMSAPassword in BloodHound
üß© Real-World Attack Scenarios
Scenario	What You Do
Helpdesk user can reset passwords	Look for ForceChangePassword on higher-priv users
IT staff can manage group memberships	Abuse AddMember or GenericWrite on groups
Legacy misconfig gives rights to low-priv user	Abuse any of GenericWrite/All/etc.
Can read GMSA passwords	Use GMSAPasswordReader to dump creds
Add SPN to user	Use GenericWrite ‚Üí SPN ‚Üí Kerberoast
‚ö†Ô∏è Pro Tips
Always Check Encryption Type: For SPN-related attacks, RC4 (etype 23) is easier to crack. AES (etype 18) is slower.

BloodHound Edges Are Your Friends: AddMember, ForceChangePassword, GenericWrite, etc. ‚Üí these are signals of potential abuse.

Document EVERYTHING: Especially if doing destructive actions like password resets.

Always revert changes, and highlight them in your report.

üõ°Ô∏è Detection & Mitigation (Blue Team Angle)
Detection Method	What to Watch For
Event 4720 / 4722 / 4723 / 4724	Password resets or account creations
Event 4732 / 4756	Group membership changes
Event 4662	ACL changes on directory objects
BloodHound exports	Review for excessive rights like GenericAll, WriteDACL
üîö Summary: How to Think About ACEs in a Pentest
ACEs = ‚ÄúWho can do what to what?‚Äù

Focus on rights that change objects, not just read/view access.

Look for paths like:

Can reset ‚Üí Own the user

Can modify group ‚Üí Join elevated group

Can modify ACLs ‚Üí Grant yourself control

